1 Introduction

This project examines the condition of various bridges in the US. The dataset has information about the bridge condition and some covariates that can help in explaining that condition. This report summarizes the process of exploratory data analysis (EDA), proposing a linear regression model with its interpretation and diagnostics, and finally make some prediction for new data. The variables in the dataset are as follows:

Variable Description
Structure_id Identification key
Urban Whether the bridge is in an urban or rural area
Year The year the bridge was built
Lanes_on Number of traffic lanes on the bridge
AverageDaily The average daily traffic (number of vehicles)
Historic Whether the bridge is historic
Material The dominant material the bridge is made from
Spans Number of spans of the bridge
Length The length of the bridge (m)
Width The width of the bridge (m)
Trucks_percent The percentage of traffic made up of trucks

3 Data Preparation

We now load the data, assuming that the two .csv files are in data folder. Based on the dataset description, we know that Urban, Historic, and Material are categorical covariates, which corresponds to factor in R.

data <- read_csv("data/group_04.csv", col_types = cols(
  Urban = col_factor(),
  Historic = col_factor(),
  Material = col_factor(),
))

We now take a quick look at summary of the data. As we can see, there are 10 covariates, 3 of which are categorical.

4 Exploratory Data Analysis

4.1 High level overview

4.1.1 Numerical covariates

We first take a look at the numeric covariates and their distribution. To achieve this, we plot their histograms.

data |> 
  select(where(is.numeric), -c(Condition)) |> 
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "covariate") |> 
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(x=value)) +
  facet_wrap(~covariate, scales = "free", nrow=3)
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value `binwidth`.

From the plots, we can see that the distributions of the covariates are fairly skewed, especially AverageDaily, Length, Width and Spans, where the range of the values is very wide but most of them fall into a very small area, specifically near zero. This may require a log transformation to make the data more symmetrical.

We now focus our attention on the response variable, Condition, which deserves its own plot.

data |> 
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = Condition), binwidth = 1)

We can see that the distribution is symmetrical around 21. Next, we examine the correlation between numerical covariates and the response variable.

GGally::ggcorr(data)
Warning: data in columns Structure_id, Urban, Historic, and Material are not numeric and
were ignored

It can be seen that Year is the only covariate that has relatively high correlation with the response variable Condition. We expect that older bridges have worse condition than new ones, which we will inspect in the following sections.

As for the correlation between covariates, we notice that Lanes_on and Width has remarkably high positive correlation, while other pairs such as Lanes_on and AverageDaily, Length and Spans and Width and AverageDaily shows moderately positive correlation. On the other hand, Year and Trucks_percent has moderately negative correlation, indicating that more trucks cross older bridges.

4.1.2 Categorical covariates

There are three categorical covariates in the dataset, namely Historic, Urban and Material. First, we plot the heat map of counts for Historic and Material corresponding to the levels of Urban.

data |> 
  count(Historic, Material, Urban) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = Historic, y = Material, fill = n)) +
  geom_tile() +
  geom_text(aes(label = n), color = "white", fontface = "bold") +
  facet_grid(. ~ Urban) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "navy", high = "orange") +
  labs(title = "Heatmap of counts")

We now examine the categorical covariates and their relationship with the response variable.

data |> 
  select(!where(is.numeric) & !Structure_id, Condition) |> 
  pivot_longer(!Condition, names_to = "covariate", values_to = "value") |> 
  ggplot() +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = value, y = Condition)) +
  facet_wrap(~covariate, scales = "free", nrow = 2) +
  coord_flip()

As observed from the box plots, bridges with Unknown Historic have fairly higher condition than other levels, while bridges made of Timber has slightly worse condition. In terms of Urban, there is no significant variation in the condition between two levels.

4.2 Do newer bridges have better condition?

As suggested from the correlation matrix, we now plot the Year against the mean of Condition to verify if newer bridges really have better condition.

data |> 
  group_by(Year) |> 
  summarize(Condition = mean(Condition)) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = Condition)) +
  geom_line()

This confirms our expectation that bridges built more recently have better condition. However, we notice that the condition suddenly drops for bridges built between between 1900 and 1925. Perhaps we should examine what is going on in these years?

data |> 
  filter(Year > 1900, Year < 1925, Condition < 18) |> 
  select(where(is.numeric)) |> 
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "covariate") |> 
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = value)) +
  facet_wrap(~covariate, scales = "free")
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value `binwidth`.
data |> 
  filter(Year > 1900, Year < 1925, Condition < 18) |> 
  select(!where(is.numeric) & !Structure_id, Condition) |> 
  pivot_longer(!Condition, names_to = "covariate", values_to = "value") |>

5 Methods

5.1 Multiple linear regression with all covariates, no interaction

5.1.1 Model fitting

We first fit a standard linear regression model using all the covariates, where the categorical covariates are coded using dummy variables.

model <- lm(Condition ~ ., data = select(data, -Structure_id))
summary(model)

5.1.2 Model interpretation

  • An \(R^2\) value of 0.4652 means that the model is only able to explain 46.52% of the variance in the response.
  • The low p-value for the F-statistic suggests that the model helps explain some of the variance compared to the null model.
  • As for the covariates:
    • We first call our attention to the high p-values of coefficients corresponding to Urban level of Urban covariate and Other level of Material covariate. High p-values suggest that we should retain the null hypothesis that their coefficient is zero. In the context of dummy variable coding, this means that there is no significant change in the response (Condition) when we move from the reference level (in this case, Rural and Concrete respectively) to the corresponding level (Urban and Other). This is also reflected in the exploratory data analysis plots earlier.
    • Despite having very low p-values, which means statistical significance, some covariates, namely AverageDaily, Length, Width, Spans and Trucks_percent have very small coefficients (and also very small standard error, which leads to low p-values). We can further examine this by computing the confidence intervals for each covariate.
confint(model)

Due to these small coefficients, AverageDaily, Length, Width, Spans and Trucks_percent may not contribute very much to the model, unless their values are large enough. This is indeed the case for some observations when we look at the histograms in the exploratory data analysis section. Therefore, these extremely high values could be influential to the model, which is examined in the next section.
